{{Shinto |Name = Oyama Shrine |religious_affiliation = [[:en:Shinto|Shinto]] |image = [[File:Ooyama Jinja (Shiraoka).JPG|250px|Oyama Shrine]] |location = [[Saitama Prefecture]] [[Shiraoka City]] Shibayama 1021 |coordinates = {{Coord|36|02|07.1|N|139|36|38.7|E|display=inline,title}} |deity = [[:en:Emperor Ōjin|Ojin Tennō]]; {{ill|Takeminakata|ja|建御名方命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeminakata|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to タケミナカタ}} |type = Village shrine |creation = Azuchi–Momoyama period |alternative names = Shibayama Suwa Hachiman Shrine |festival = Spring Festival: April 15; Aokashi Festival: May 14 (currently May 4); Gion Festival: Second Saturday in July; Autumn Festival: October 14; Akara-Kashi Festival: November 15 }} '''Otokone Shrine''' is a Shinto shrine located in Shiraoka City, Saitama Prefecture. == Overview == It is the largest shrine in Shiraoka and serves as the center for local festivals. == Deities == * [[:en:Emperor Ōjin|Ojin Tennō]] * {{ill|Takeminakata|ja|建御名方命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeminakata|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to タケミナカタ}} * {{ill|Ikaraho-no-mikoto|ja|伊許保止命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikaraho-no-mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} – Ancestor of the local Awa deity. == History == According to tradition, the shrine was founded during the Azuchi–Momoyama period by Sasaki Hidetuna, who enshrined both a Suwa shrine and a Hachiman shrine. After the decline of the Sasaki clan, the shrine fell into disrepair until it was restored by local hatamoto Amano Yasuhiro. In 1873 (Meiji 6), it was classified as a village shrine under the modern shrine Ranking system. In 1944 (Shōwa 19), it was renamed Oyama Shrine. Although the original village name later disappeared, some local authorities and the Shiraoka Tourism Association continue to refer to it as "Shibayama Suwa Hachiman Shrine." == Cultural Properties == The votive plaques (ema) at the shrine are designated cultural properties by Shiraoka City. == Access == It is located about a 20‑minute walk from the Ue Hirano bus stop. == See Also == * [[:en:List of Shinto shrines|List of Shinto shrines]] * [[Sannō shrines]] * [[Gion Faith|Gion faith]] == External Links == * [https://sannoushrinenoto.wixsite.com/mysite Official website]
